        (document.getElementsByTagName('HEAD')[0] || document.getElementsByTagName('BODY')[0]).appendChild(s);
    }());
</script></aside><h2><a href="lesson-23-consonants-part-7-and">Lesson #23: Consonants part 7: श sha, ष sha, स sa and ह ha</a></h2><div class="caption clearfix rte"><p>Finally then we have made it to the very last group of Hindi consonants. How are you feeling about it? Be sure to head back to the <a href="../../consonants">Consonants Section</a> if you feel that you&rsquo;ve forgotten anything. Are you ready to get going then? Here goes, here&rsquo;s the consonants we&rsquo;re going to be learning today&hellip;&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/e868936d50d7f69fe16fb1125b54a3f9/tumblr_inline_n57qmaC7u21qzfx8l.png"></p><p>The first three letter of this group are called the sibilants&nbsp;and the final letter is what&rsquo;s called an aspirate. So let&rsquo;s get into it. Our first letter for today is&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/6a1dda093c75485f8eb3cf4a119b491b/tumblr_inline_n57qzkWduL1qzfx8l.png">&nbsp;<em>sha</em> &nbsp; &nbsp; <iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/149212682&amp;%20%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p>This is the letter <big><big>&#2358;</big></big> <em>sha</em>. This is pronounced just like the &ldquo;sh&rdquo; in English words like &ldquo;sheep&rdquo; or &ldquo;ship&rdquo;. Use the audio to hear it pronounced! This letter looks a bit like a 2 with a line on the side of it, can you see?&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/90a56e71a908be12e8efbe542295115a/tumblr_inline_n57rkyVnik1qzfx8l.jpg"><br><small><small><a href="http://t.umblr.com/redirect?z=http%3A%2F%2Fcommons.wikimedia.org%2Fwiki%2FFile%3AThe_Indian_Wedding_Story.jpg%3Fuselang%3Den-gb&amp;t=YmI0MDk5NDJlMzM3MGUxYzIwNTg4ZDQ1ZTBhOGIzODA2ZmRmNDhjMix0U2hQYm05dQ%3D%3D&amp;b=t%3Ahf3yIetu6VvjxJqY6DH92g&amp;p=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.learning-hindi.com%2Fpost%2F908470587%2Flesson-23-consonants-part-7-%E0%A4%B6-sha-%E0%A4%B7-sha-%E0%A4%B8-sa&amp;m=0">Image by Wikicommons</a>&nbsp;-&nbsp;under a CC-BY-SA 3.0 licence.</small></small></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2358;&#2366;&#2342;&#2368;</big></big><span>&nbsp;</span><em>shaadee - </em>Wedding.&nbsp;</p><p>Weddings are always a very big celebration in India! The Hindi word for wedding is&nbsp;<big><big>&#2358;&#2366;&#2342;&#2368;</big></big><span>&nbsp;</span><em>shaadee</em>. Can you see our new letter here? Be sure to listen to the audio too. Let&rsquo;s keep going then&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/71de5898ffbd21b6af21a713bd95ca5e/tumblr_inline_n57scrRJvC1qzfx8l.png">&nbsp;<em>sha</em> &nbsp; &nbsp; <iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/149212822&amp;%20%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p>This is the letter <big><big>&#2359;</big></big> <em>sha</em>. This letter is pronounced exactly the same as&nbsp;<big><big>&#2358;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>sha</em>. Historically&nbsp;<big><big>&#2359;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>sha </em>was pronounced as a retroflex consonant, with the tongue rolled back, but this is very rare these days.&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/3a19e2a8a9006e73bce1790f58555bfd/tumblr_inline_n57swd5fR01qzfx8l.png">&nbsp;<big><big>&#2349;&#2366;&#2359;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>bhaashaa -&nbsp;</em>Language.&nbsp;</p><p>The word for language in Hindi is&nbsp;<big><big>&#2349;&#2366;&#2359;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>bhaashaa. </em>Can you see our new letter here? As always don&rsquo;t forget to use the audio above.&nbsp;</p><p>Be careful with the letters&nbsp;<big><big>&#2358;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>sha&nbsp;</em>and&nbsp;<big><big>&#2359;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>sha - </em>they both sound identical but there is always only one correct way to spell a word. This is just like in English how we spell &ldquo;cat&rdquo; with a &ldquo;c&rdquo; and not as &ldquo;kat&rdquo;! The letter&nbsp;<big><big>&#2359;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>sha </em>is not as common and is only found in Hindi words that come from Sanskrit. Ok, ready to move on?&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/1eb212bc7cb9abe20c889b8fae35080a/tumblr_inline_n57tjrEeGJ1qzfx8l.png"><span>&nbsp;</span><em>sa</em><span> &nbsp; &nbsp; </span><iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/149212910&amp;%20%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p>This is the letter <big><big>&#2360;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>sa</em>. This letter is another one that&rsquo;s super easy to pronounce - it sounds exactly like the normal English &ldquo;s&rdquo; like in &ldquo;seat&rdquo; or &ldquo;sing&rdquo;. Listen to the audio above to hear it. Here&rsquo;s an example word&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/fd1b27673efa6e7880e6339bcf053e91/tumblr_inline_n57twuUTqc1qzfx8l.png"><span>&nbsp;</span><big><big>&#2360;&#2370;&#2352;&#2332;</big></big><span>&nbsp;</span><em>sooraj -&nbsp;</em><span>Sun.&nbsp;</span></p><p>Can you see our new letter here? Nice one! Ok let&rsquo;s move on to our very last letter of the very last group then! Here goes&hellip;</p><p class="center"><span><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/1320b6b1dc94afd841b32099fe3d4cdf/tumblr_inline_n57tz2yWFt1qzfx8l.png">&nbsp;</span><span>&nbsp;</span><em>ha</em><span> &nbsp; &nbsp; </span><iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/149213098&amp;%20%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p>This is the letter <big><big>&#2361;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>ha</em>. This letter again sounds like the English &ldquo;h&rdquo;, like in &ldquo;hand&rdquo; or &ldquo;help&rdquo;. The letter looks a bit like a funny claw trying to grab on to something, don&rsquo;t you think?&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/cb19c49b04c1ea76e11f1939900f7ff7/tumblr_inline_n57uq0i5BS1qzfx8l.png"><span>&nbsp;</span><big><big>&#2361;&#2366;&#2341;</big></big><span>&nbsp;</span><em>haath - </em>Hand<span>.&nbsp;</span></p><p>Can you see our new letter in the word&nbsp;<big><big>&#2361;&#2366;&#2341;</big></big><span>&nbsp;</span><em>haath</em>? Excellent! Listen to the audio above to hear the word pronounced!&nbsp;</p><p>Now before we finish there&rsquo;s one more thing we need to learn. Some Hindi speakers will pronounce some words with <big><big>&#2361;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>ha&nbsp;</em>differently to what we might expect. The rules for this are easy - if we have the vowel sound&nbsp;<big><big>&#2309;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>a </em>both before and after the letter&nbsp;<big><big>&#2361;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>ha </em>in a word then some speakers in casual conversation change both&nbsp;<big><big>&#2309;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>a</em>&nbsp;sounds to something close to the vowel <big><big>&#2320;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>ai. </em>Let me give you an example&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/d2fd83eb53c6e03d52d9e01461488dac/tumblr_inline_n57v9ktzLa1qzfx8l.png"><span>&nbsp;</span><big><big>&#2348;&#2361;&#2344;</big></big><span>&nbsp;</span><em>bahan - </em>Sister<span>.&nbsp;</span></p><p>The Hindi word&nbsp;<big><big>&#2348;&#2361;&#2344;</big></big><span>&nbsp;</span><em>bahan </em>means sister. Click the audio above, next to the letter&nbsp;<big><big>&#2361;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>ha</em>, to hear two different ways to pronounce <big><big>&#2348;&#2361;&#2344;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>bahan</em>: first in the standard <em>bahan</em>&nbsp;(in its technically correct form) and second as &nbsp;<em>baihain</em>&nbsp;(in its casual form used by some Hindi speakers). You can happily use either pronunciation but just be aware that some people pronounce it as&nbsp;<em>baihain</em>.</p><p>Phew, that&rsquo;s it! Wow. You&rsquo;ve now learnt all of the Hindi consonants! How does it feel? Give your self a pat on the back.</p><p>Unfortunately there&rsquo;s still quite a bit more we need to learn before we&rsquo;ve mastered everything to know about Hindi consonants, so head on back to the <a href="../../consonants">Consonants Section </a>and keep learning!&nbsp;</p><p><a href="../../consonants">Click to go back to the Consonants Section</a>.&nbsp;</p></div><aside class="post-footer"><div class="tags"><span>Tags:</span><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/consonants">consonants</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/aug2010">aug2010</a> </div><div class="bottom"><div class="like_button" data-post-id="908470587" data-blog-name="learninghindi" id="like_button_908470587"><iframe id="like_iframe_908470587" src="http://assets.tumblr.com/assets/html/like_iframe.html?_v=5716f9145cbbcc5e21aa13229de5d4ed#name=learninghindi&amp;post_id=908470587&amp;color=grey&amp;rk=tShPbm9u" scrolling="no" width="16" height="16" frameborder="0" class="like_toggle" allowTransparency="true" name="like_iframe_908470587"></iframe></div><a href="https://www.tumblr.com/reblog/908470587/tShPbm9u" class="reblog_button"style="display: block;width:16px;height:16px;"><svg width="100%" height="100%" viewBox="0 0 21 21" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink